<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p>Deep learning models have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in various domains, including image recognition, natural language processing, and autonomous vehicles. However, the deployment of these models in real-world scenarios poses unique challenges and risks that need to be addressed to ensure reliable and unbiased decision-making.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Challenges for Robust Deep Learning:</strong> One significant challenge in deep learning is algorithmic bias, where models exhibit discriminatory behaviour due to biases in the training data. Class imbalance and latent feature imbalance can also impact model performance and fairness. Addressing these challenges requires novel approaches that go beyond traditional training methodologies.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>What is Algorithmic Bias?</strong> Algorithmic bias refers to the phenomenon where AI systems produce discriminatory or unfair outcomes due to biases in the data or training process. It can perpetuate societal inequalities and lead to biased decisions in critical areas such as hiring, lending, and criminal justice. Understanding and mitigating algorithmic bias is crucial for building trustworthy AI systems.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

