<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Uncertainty in Deep Learning:</strong> Uncertainty estimation is crucial for building robust and trustworthy AI systems. We discuss the different types of uncertainty in AI, namely aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty, and their significance in decision-making. Estimating and quantifying uncertainty can enhance the transparency and reliability of AI systems.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Estimating Aleatoric Uncertainty:</strong> Aleatoric uncertainty captures the inherent noise and variability in the data. We explore methods for estimating aleatoric uncertainty, such as modelling noise directly or using ensemble approaches. By understanding and quantifying aleatoric uncertainty, AI systems can make more informed and cautious decisions.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Estimating Epistemic Uncertainty:</strong> Epistemic uncertainty captures uncertainty arising from model limitations and lack of knowledge. We discuss techniques for estimating epistemic uncertainty, including Bayesian approaches and Monte Carlo dropout. By accounting for epistemic uncertainty, AI systems can make more robust and calibrated predictions.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Evidential Deep Learning:</strong> Evidential deep learning is an emerging paradigm that combines the strengths of Bayesian modelling and deep learning. It enables the estimation of both aleatoric and epistemic uncertainty, providing a comprehensive framework for robust and trustworthy AI systems.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

<!-- wp:paragraph -->
<p><strong>Recap of Challenges:</strong> We recap the challenges discussed, emphasizing the importance of addressing algorithmic bias, class imbalance, latent feature imbalance, and uncertainty estimation to ensure robust and trustworthy deep learning.</p>
<!-- /wp:paragraph -->

